{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b62bfe72-d49f-4813-8502-a03ef01c082a","content":"Here's the analysis of evaluation performance issues in this project:\n\n## Evaluation Performance Issues Found\n\n### 1. File I/O Property Function (High Impact)\n**Line 13 in `EvalHeavy.csproj`:**\n```xml\n<BuildNotes>$([System.IO.File]::ReadAllText('build-notes.txt'))</BuildNotes>\n```\nReading files via property functions executes during **every evaluation** (design-time builds, IDE refreshes, etc.). This is one of the most expensive evaluation-time operations.\n\n**Fix:** Move this to a target with `Inputs/Outputs` so it only runs during execution, or use a build task instead.\n\n### 2. Overly Broad Glob Pattern (Medium Impact)\n**Line 9:**\n```xml\n<AdditionalFiles Include=\"**\\*.*\" Exclude=\"**\\bin\\**;**\\obj\\**\" />\n```\nThis walks the **entire directory tree** at evaluation time. If `node_modules`, `.git`, or other large directories exist, this causes severe slowdowns. The glob also lacks exclusions for common heavy folders.\n\n**Fix:** Add more exclusions via `DefaultItemExcludes`, or narrow the glob to specific extensions/directories.\n\n### 3. Chained Import Depth (Low-Medium Impact)\nThe import chain `level1.props → level2.props → level3.props` is 3 levels deep. While modest here, this pattern scales poorly. Each import adds evaluation overhead and makes preprocessing output harder to trace.\n\n---\n\n**Summary:** The biggest wins are eliminating the `File::ReadAllText` property function and tightening the glob pattern. These two alone likely account for most evaluation overhead.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"97727550-b321-4a0a-893b-19b230c8540c","outputTokens":393,"requestId":"1901:287A16:149C71D:1730CF1:6A067545"},"id":"d018e37a-5662-4350-81d0-6de2335321fc","timestamp":"2026-05-15T01:22:24.785Z","parentId":"ff4e4ab1-2c9d-4cdf-bc9b-acb7ff918d5f"}
